  "$comment": "Cross-language ATIF trajectory conformance vectors. The Rust types in crates/mira-eval/src/trajectory.rs are the source of truth: `Trajectory::project_into` defines how the Transcript flat fields (final_response, tool_calls, tool_calls_count, iterations, usage) are derived from a trajectory, hand-mirrored by sdks/python/mira/trajectory.py and sdks/typescript/src/trajectory.ts. Each case carries one ATIF document; every runner asserts it (1) parses — or is rejected when `rejects` is set (only the ATIF-v1.x schema_version prefix is accepted), (2) round-trips (re-serializing and re-parsing yields the same document, `extra` maps included; unknown fields are tolerated on parse, per the crate-wide lenient-serde posture), and (3) projects onto the pinned `projection`. Three runners, one fixture (the scorers.json pattern): crates/mira-eval/tests/trajectory_conformance.rs (the oracle), sdks/python/tests/test_trajectory_conformance.py, sdks/typescript/tests/trajectory-conformance.test.mjs. The 'rfc worked example' case is the worked example from harbor RFC 0001 (Section IV), verbatim.",
